    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense. I saw a note in a forum saying that blockages can be a huge issue for these tubes. What kind of things usually cause those blockages, and how much does it affect the readings?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Blockages in a pitot tube are most commonly caused by insects, ice in cold weather, or dirt/sand splashing from the skins below during low passes. If the forward-facing port gets completely clogged, the instrument will read zero airspeed even when the aircraft is moving. Partial obstructions can also occur, leading to erratic or inaccurate readings that complicate flight operations significantly.",
      "source": "target",
